The paper deals with designing dynamic graph algorithms in minor-free graphs, which is a topic in the area of data structures (cs.DS) and computational geometry (cs.CG). The use of vertex sparsification, a tool for compressing large graphs, suggests that the paper may also be relevant to numerical analysis (cs.NA) and discrete mathematics (cs.DM). Finally, the paper presents upper and lower bounds for maintaining the energy of electrical flows, which is a problem in the area of computational complexity (cs.CC).
